{Already in the first article, we have found out that no matter how
interesting play gets, there is a certain drawish tendency in the Catalan
opening. If White does everything right his play is more pleasant, either
tactically, or strategically, but he could mainly hope for practical winning
chances. But this is the fate of most modern openings after all. In this
article, we will examine an apparently dry, yet, in my opinion, interesting
and deep, situation. One of Black's main hopes for equalizing is exchanging
the c- and d-pawns and then as many pieces as possible. But typically White is
able to keep a tiny edge due to his slight advance in development. The limit
between drawish and promising endings of this kind is very tiny and once again
we can mainly speak about practical chances, meaning that in certain position
White should count on winning, say, 4-5 games out of 10. We will start with a
classical example with a reigning World champion playing the part of the
victim.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2
a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {One of the main Catalan tabyias. Black seems to have
comfortable play, but he needs being careful, as after the desired break ...
c7-c5 and the probable exchange of the light-squared bishops his queenside
will be slightly weak.} 10. Bf4 Nd5 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 Nd7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14.
Ne4 c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. Qxc5 Bxc5 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. Ne5 Bxg2 20.
Kxg2 {[#]We reached a highly interesting position. The fact that a player of
Karpov's caliber wasn't able to defend this apparently simple ending is a
clear hint that there are many hidden subtleties in it. I shall try to uncover
at least some of them. White's advantage consists of two main details. First
of all, he managed to occupy both open lines, which will give him the
possibility of blackmailing the opponent in several ways. Secondly, given the
multitude of weak squares, his knight is more useful for the moment than the
black bishop.} f6 $6 ({Against} 20... Rc7 {Ugrinovic,D suggests} 21. Nd3 Bd6
22. Rxc7 Bxc7 23. Rc1 $14 {His evaluation seems to be correct: the rook
controls the open c-file while the knight occupies the perfect d3-square,
preventing any counterplay along the d-line.}) (20... Rc7 {However, even more
interesting is Moiseejev's and Ravinsky's suggestion:} 21. b4 $1 Bd6 22. Rxc7
Bxc7 23. Nxf7 Bxf4 24. Nd8 e5 25. Ne6 Kf7 26. Rd6 $16 {threatening e2-e3 or
Nc7.}) ({Black's best defense would have been} 20... Be7 {possibly followed by
...Bf6.}) 21. Nf3 ({In many situations the best square for the knight is d3,
but in this concrete position,} 21. Nd3 {would make less sense because it
would block the access of the own rook to Black's seventh rank.}) 21... Bf8 {
This is a forced move, preventing White from occupying the seventh rank. We
see a curious situation: for the moment, neither of the sides can start
concrete actions. The exchange of rooks is out of question for both players.
Black cannot activate his king because this would allow Rd7+. This mutual
pseudo-zugzwang clearly favors White, who has better possibilities of making
small improvements in his position.} 22. e3 g6 {[#]} 23. b3 {Ribli understands
that he has to open one more file on the queenside; otherwise, the rooks will
watch each other along the c-file eternally. However, since he was going to
play h3 anyway on the next move, the direct 23.h3 might have been a bit better,
not weakening yet the queenside dark squares.} Bb4 ({Why did Karpov refrain
from the tempting} 23... Ba3 {which would have left him with the control of
the c-file after} 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 {? The answer is that on a3 the bishop is
misplaced, which can be seen in the variation} 25. Rd7 Rc2 26. Ra7 Rxa2 27.
Rxa6 $16 {when the weakness of the e6 and b5 pawns, as well as the pin on the
a-file, make life difficult for Black.}) 24. h3 {Another little useful move.
Although its benefits are not clear yet, it is better to keep such isloated
pawns on squares of opposite colour with the bishop's, in order to avoid
losses of tempo in case of an eventual forced variation.} Kf8 {It might look
as if as a consequence of White's 23rd move, Black finally has some
constructive plan. However, White's next move will prove that this is only
partially true.} 25. Nd4 Kf7 ({Not, of course,} 25... Ke7 $4 26. Nc6+ $18) 26.
a4 {Opening another queenside line.} bxa4 27. bxa4 {[#]} Bc5 {Ugrinovic puts
his blame for Black's further problems on this move.} ({He recommends} 27... a5
{, maintaining the b-line closed. However, this move would place a pawn on a
dark square, which would be bad in case of massive simplifications. Besides,
as mentioned by Neishtadt,} 28. Nb5 {White will make progress anyway. First of
all, Rd7 is threatened while after} Ke7 29. Nc7 Rab8 (29... Ra7 $2 30. Nd5+ $1
$18) 30. Rc6 {the weaknesses on the sixth rank will prove decisive.}) 28. Rc4
Ba3 (28... Bxd4 29. Rcxd4 Re8 30. Rb4 $16 {Ugrinovic,D. White's domination of
the open files as well as the weaknesses on e6 and, especially, a6, make
Black's position dificult}) 29. Rxc8 Rxc8 30. Rb1 {Here is where the newly
created open line proves useful for White.} Rc4 (30... Rc7 31. Rb8 {Ugrinovic,D
}) 31. Rb7+ Be7 32. Ra7 $1 {In the next phase of the game, White will have
some small tactical tricks to crown his entire strategy.} e5 {The only move.} (
32... Rxa4 $2 33. Nc6 $18) 33. fxe5 fxe5 34. Nf3 Rxa4 35. Nxe5+ Kf6 36. Nc6 Bc5
37. Rxh7 Ra2 38. Kf3 a5 {[#]As the game shows the a-pawn is too slow to bother
White, who can create dangerous threats on the opposite wing.} 39. h4 {A very
subtle move, bearing an idea that will become obvious one move later.} a4 40.
Ke4 $1 {The control of the g5 square was essential in order to make this move
possible. The pawn is taboo, because of the terrible threat Nd8 threatening
mate.} Bf8 {Black has to allow the rook occupy the a7 square.} (40... Rxf2 $2 {
loses the rook to} 41. Nd8 g5 42. Rf7+ Kg6 43. Rxf2 $18) ({There is no time for
} 40... a3 {either:} 41. Nd8 g5 42. h5 g4 43. Rf7+ Kg5 44. Ne6+ Kxh5 45. Nxc5
$18) {[#]} 41. Ra7 $6 {The first move after the time control is, as in so many
cases, inaccurate.} ({The careless} 41. f4 Bg7 $1 {would cage the rook.}) ({
But the most precise move, requiring accurate calculating or just intuition,
was} 41. Ne5 Bg7 42. Ng4+ Kf7 43. h5 $1 {Freeing the rook in time.} Kg8 {
Trying to keep the rook passive as long as possible.} 44. hxg6 Rc2 45. Rh5 Rc4+
46. Kf3 Bc3 47. Rb5 Kg7 (47... a3 48. Rb8+ Kg7 49. Ra8 Bb2 50. Ra7+ Kxg6 51.
Rxa3 $1 {wins easily}) 48. Rb7+ Kxg6 49. Rb6+ Kg5 (49... Kg7 50. Ra6 {should
win as the a-pawn is under control and the white pawns can slowly advance.})
50. Rb5+ Kg6 (50... Kh4 51. Ne5 {threatening Ng6# also forces the exchange.})
51. Ne5+ Bxe5 52. Rxe5 {followed by Ra5 when White should win.}) {[#]} 41...
Bd6 $6 ({Karpov probably refrained from} 41... Rxf2 $1 {due to} 42. Ne5 {
missing} Rb2 $1 (42... Ke6 {does not work:} 43. Ra6+ Ke7 44. Nxg6+ Ke8 45. Nxf8
Kxf8 46. Rxa4 {winning.}) 43. Ra6+ Kg7 44. Rxg6+ Kh7 45. Ra6 a3 $14 {The
a-pawn has turned dangerous while White does not have connected pawns as in
the rpevious lines.}) 42. f4 $16 Rh2 43. Ra6 Kf7 44. Ne5+ $6 (44. Rxa4 Rxh4 45.
Kd5 $18 {is more accurate.} Bf8 46. Ne5+ Kg7 47. Ra7+ {winning the g6-pawn.})
44... Bxe5 45. Kxe5 {[#]} Kg7 $2 (45... Rxh4 46. Ra7+ Kg8 47. Rxa4 {looks
hopeless as Black's pieces are awfully misplaced but actually Black should
hold after} Rh3 48. e4 Rh4) 46. Ra7+ Kh6 47. Rxa4 Rxh4 48. Kf6 {Now it is all
over, as White has a more favorable version of the aforementioned ending.} Rh5
49. e4 Rh4 50. e5 Rh5 51. e6 Rf5+ 52. Ke7 Kg7 53. Kd6 Rf8 54. Ra7+ Kf6 55. Rd7
(55. Rd7 {Black is in Zugzwang:} g5 (55... Ra8 56. Rf7#) (55... Kf5 56. Rf7+)
56. fxg5+ Kxg5 57. e7 $18) 1-0

