{Another typical situation with the same endgame structure features knights on
both sides (instead of knight versus bishop) with or without rooks on board.
In the following game another World champion (true, former already) found
himself in big trouble.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6.
c4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Rc8 12. Bxf6 Nxf6
13. Nb3 Be4 14. Qc3 Nd5 15. Qd2 c5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. dxc5 Rxc5 18. Rac1 Rxc1
19. Rxc1 {[#]} Nf6 $6 {This move leads to a very pleasant ending for White.
The game is, however, suggestive of Black's defensive resources.} 20. Qxd8 Rxd8
21. Ne5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Ne8 $5 {Facing a difficult position, Tal starts
defending very accurately. The knight seems passive on e8, of course, but it
serves the concrete purpose of defending the crucial c7 and d6 squares, thus
preventing the penetration of the white rook.} 23. Nd3 Kf8 {The next emergency
is to bring the king to the center. Black has to compensate by a material
superiority the better coordination of the white army.} 24. Rc6 Rd6 25. Rc8 Ke7
{[#]} 26. Rb8 $1 {The b-line offers the best mobility to the rook.} ({For
instance, after} 26. Ra8 Nc7 {the rook would be quite restricted in its
actions.}) 26... Nc7 ({The first example of White's superior coordination is} 
26... Kd7 $2 27. Ne5+ Ke7 28. Rb7+ $16 Kf6 $6 29. f4 $1 $18) 27. f4 {Using
this moment of "respiro", White wins space in the center.} Rd8 28. Rb7 $1 (28.
Rb6 {would lead nowhere:} Rd6 $1) 28... Kd7 29. Rb6 {It is remarkable how
invulnerable the white rook feels, although optically it is surrounded by
enemy forces.} Kc8 {Tal prepares the activation of the rook.} ({Black has to
be very careful. White's domination can irrump from one moment to another into
tactical fireworks:} 29... a5 $6 30. Ne5+ Kc8 31. Nc6 Rd6 (31... Rd2 $2 {
loses the rook to} 32. Rb8+ Kd7 33. Rd8+ $18) 32. Rb8+ Kd7 33. Ne5+ Ke7 34. Rb7
{and Black loses material for instance} Kd8 35. Nxf7+ $18) 30. Kf3 {[#]} a5 $5
{Black cannot wait passively until White builds up a massive space advantage
with g4-g5.} 31. b3 {preventing 31...a4, which would allow Black to defend
both his queenside pawns.} Rd5 32. Ne5 {This active continuation should have
offered White a large advantage after Black's inaccurate defense.} ({There was
nothing wrong with the neutral} 32. g4 $5) 32... f6 33. Nc6 Rd6 $6 (33... Rh5 {
offered better chances for successful defense.} 34. Nxa5 (34. h4 b4 $11 {
allows Black consolidating.}) 34... Rxh2 35. Nc6 Rh5 {True, White's position
remains more pleasant, but at least Black would have had exchanged one of his
weak pawns.} 36. Na7+ Kd7 37. Rb7 Kd6 38. b4 {and Black keeps being tied up to
the defense of the b5-pawn with his pieces enjoying a narrow mobility.}) {[#]}
34. Na7+ $6 {Having reached a maximum of activity, Larsen should have
transformed it in some concrete advantage, such as a small material gain. He
might have forgotten that this kind of domination with an inferior number of
pieces tend to evaporate.} (34. Rb8+ $1 Kd7 35. Nxa5 {when} Rd2 36. a4 Ra2 {
would fail to} 37. Nb7 $1 $16 {indirectly defending a4.}) 34... Kd7 35. Rb7 Rd5
$1 ({Larsen might have underestimated this move. If} 35... b4 36. Nb5 Rc6 37.
Ra7 {Wite soon wins the a5-pawn. with some practical chances to convert it.}) {
[#]} 36. a4 $6 ({This leads to an obvious draw. White would have retained the
long-term control with} 36. a3 $1 {immobilizing both black queenside pawns.})
36... bxa4 37. bxa4 Kd8 38. e3 Rc5 39. Nb5 Kc8 ({Black could have already
forced a draw with} 39... Nxb5 40. axb5 Rc7 41. Rb8+ Rc8 $11) 40. Nd6+ Kd7 41.
Ne4 Rc4 42. Ra7 f5 43. Nd2 Rxa4 44. Nb3 Ra2 45. h4 a4 46. Rxa4 $1 1/2-1/2

