{The third possible minor pieces duel in this type of ending is bishop versus
bishop. This usually is less interesting and Black would need making some sort
of early concession in order to make White's chances realistic.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Bg2 a6 7. Nc3 Rb8 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3
Bb7 10. O-O c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bf4 Rc8 13. Rad1 {[#]Andersson played this
system many times without proving anything real out of the opening. But his
opponents sometimes lost their patience making some nervous moves handing in
White undeserved advantage.} b4 $6 {Had Milov anticipated that all minor
pieces with the exception of the dark-squared bishops would get off the board,
he would have thought twice before making this committal and unnecessary move.
Instead, he should have just castled.} 14. Na4 Be7 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qa5
17. Nxd7 Qxa4 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. b3 Qc6+ 20. Qf3 Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 {There finally
is something such an endgame specialist like Andersson can play for. In some
situations, the b4-pawn, blocked on a dark square, may turn the enemy bishop
into a "bad" one. But with just one weakness on board, Black should still be
able to hold a draw without any special problems.} Rc3+ {Not yet a significant
mistake, but abstractly this worsens Black's coordination, as he cannot
connect rooks too soon already.} ({He could have tried} 21... a5 22. Rd6 Ke7
23. Ra6 Ra8 24. Rc6 Rhd8 25. Rfc1 Bc3 26. a4 {with rather symbolic white
advantage.}) 22. Kg2 {[#]} a5 $6 ({Finally the move turning Black's position
critical. One move earlier advancing the a-pawn was safe, as his rooks got
connected soon, but under the given circumstances Black will simply be
underdeveloped. ***He should have played} 22... O-O $1 {for instance} 23. Bd6
Rfc8 24. Bxb4 Rc2 25. a4 Rxe2 {with a probable draw.}) 23. Rd6 g5 ({This
creates a new weakness without really bothering the white bishop. But if} 23...
Ke7 24. Ra6 Rd8 ({Only not} 24... Rc5 $2 25. Bd6+) 25. Rxa5 Rc2 26. Kf3 Bb2 27.
Bg5+ f6 28. Be3 {Black still faces problems.} Kf7 (28... Ba3 29. Ra7+ Rd7 30.
Rxd7+ Kxd7 31. Rd1+ Kc6 32. Rd2 {stabilizing the position with good winning
chances.}) 29. Ra7+ Kg8 30. Rb7 Ba3 ({It is not entirely clear whether White
can win the endgame arising after} 30... Bc3 31. Bc5 Rxa2 32. Bxb4 Bxb4 33.
Rxb4 {if Black defends optimally, but the seventh rank weakness certainly
favors him with respect to other similar endings.}) 31. h4 h5 {Allowing h4-h5
would leave Black very passive but the last game is no improvement.} 32. g4
hxg4+ 33. Kxg4 Rxa2 34. h5 {followed by Rg1 with a dangerous attack.}) 24. Be3
{[#]} a4 {Desperation.} (24... Ke7 25. Ra6 {is an improved version of the
previous line as g5 is many times hanging.}) 25. bxa4 O-O 26. a5 {The a-pawn
suddenly wins the game.} Ra8 27. a6 Ra3 28. a7 Rxa2 29. Rd7 Kg7 30. Rb7 Rxe2
31. Rd1 b3 32. Rb8 1-0

