{In all these games the advance of the queenside pawns left several weaknesses
behind, offering White's pieces possibilities for an intrusion. But if Black
keeps these pawns on their initial squares, there may be a delay in
development, allowing White building up his pressure on several board areas.
The next classical game is not a proper Catalan, but it features the structure
of our interest in its most typical aspects.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. d4 Nf6 4.
Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. g3 cxd4 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bb4+ 10. Bd2
Bxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Ke7 12. Bg2 Rd8 13. Ke3 {[#]White has a lead in development and
the b7-pawn is under pressure. In order to avoid landing into problems, Black
needs acting accurately. Euwe did not.} Na6 $2 ({Euwe was probably obsessed by
leaving the c8-bishop's diagonal clear, but the knight has no perspectives
here. True, the recommended} 13... e5 {may be answered with} 14. Nb3 Nc6 15.
Bxc6 $5 bxc6 16. Nc5 $14 {with a typical good knight versus bad bishop ending.}
) ({Black should have used the only drawback in White's setup, his vulnerable
king with:} 13... Nd7 {The bishop can wait while the knight becomes active
with gain of time.} 14. Rac1 Nf6 15. h3 e5 {and Black is close to equality.})
14. Rac1 $6 ({During the next couple of moves White hesitates to play f2-f4
and Black does the same with ...e6-e5.} 14. f4 $1 {might have transposed to
the game.}) 14... Rb8 15. a3 Bd7 16. f4 $1 {Finally!} f6 {[#]} 17. Be4 {
An important moment, marking the difference between the plan from the previous
examples and that from positions with the a- and b-pawns "home". Everything is
under control on the queenside but there are no immediate ways of intruding.
Therefore White hurries creating weaknesses on Black's opposite wing.} Be8 (
17... e5 $2 18. fxe5 fxe5 19. Nf3 {wins a pawn.}) (17... g6 18. h4 Be8 19. g4 {
followed by g4-g5 increases White's strategic advantage.}) ({The least evil
would have been} 17... h6 {, not offering White a clear target yet.}) 18. b4 {
Threatening b5.} Rd7 {[#]} 19. f5 $1 {White had several other good moves,
aiming at increasing the pressure, but this wins a pawn by force.} Nc7 (19...
e5 20. Ne6 $18 {attacks on g7 and threatens to win a piece with b4-b5.}) 20.
fxe6 Nxe6 21. Nxe6 Kxe6 22. Bxh7 f5 23. Rc5 g6 24. Bg8+ Kf6 25. Rhc1 {White
has won a pawn and with some technical effort the game.} Re7+ 26. Kf2 Bc6 27.
Bd5 Rbe8 28. Re1 Bxd5 29. Rxd5 g5 30. Rd6+ Ke5 31. Red1 g4 32. R1d5+ Ke4 33.
Rd4+ Ke5 34. Ke3 Re6 35. R4d5+ Kf6+ 36. Kf4 Kg6 37. Rxe6+ Rxe6 38. Re5 Ra6 39.
Rxf5 Rxa3 40. Rb5 $1 b6 41. Kxg4 1-0

