{[#]Black is very passive as his knight is tied up to the defense of the
a6-pawn and White has a considerable space advantage. With} 32... e5 {Black
tried fixing the latter problem. Evaluate this move. ***Black's decision only
made things worse. By keeping a passive policy he would have faced White with
bigger problems breaking through, while after the game move things turn simple.
} 33. Kf3 ({More restrictive was} 33. fxe5 fxe5 34. Kf3 {and Black cannot
prevent a transposition to the game, for instance:} Kf6 35. Kg4 Kg6 36. Nd7 {
wins the e5-pawn.}) 33... g6 ({Black should have tried his chance with} 33...
exf4 34. gxf4 {when White's advantage is huge, indeed, but his plan is less
clearcut than in the game.}) 34. fxe5 fxe5 35. Kg4 h6 ({The only way to fight
against the king's intrusion for if} 35... Kf6 36. Nd7+ Ke6 37. Nf8+ {wins
pawn.}) 36. h4 h5+ (36... Kf6 37. h5 Kf7 38. Nd7 {is also hopeless.}) 37. Kg5
Kg7 38. g4 hxg4 39. Kxg4 Kf6 40. a3 (40. h5 {also wins.}) 40... Kf7 41. Kg5 Kg7
42. Nd7 {Finally winning a pawn.} Ne6+ 43. Kg4 Nd4 44. Nxe5 Nc2 45. Nd7 Nxa3
46. Nc5 Nc4 47. Nxa6 Ne5+ 48. Kf4 Nd3+ 49. Ke3 Ne1 50. e5 Kf7 51. Ke4 Ng2 52.
Nc7 Nxh4 53. Nxb5 Nf5 54. Nd4 Ne7 55. b5 Nc8 56. Kd5 g5 57. Kc5 1-0

