{[#]White has the usual pressure but Black hoped to get some relief after} 
33... Kd6 {planning ...b7-b6 followed by ...f7-f6 or simply ...Nc7. How would
you continue with white?} 34. Rc3 $3 $16 {[%cal Yd3c5,Yc3b3] White clears the
c5-square, fres the knight from the task of defending the rook and keeps the
enemy king cut off the weak queenside. There are threats like e4-e5+ followed
by Nc5+ in the picture.} ({The seemingly active} 34. Rb5 $6 {allows Black
consolidating with} Kc7 $14) (34. e5+ Kd7 35. Rc3 b6 {is also nothing special,
as White has deprived himself of Ne5+.}) 34... Ra6 (34... Ke7 35. Rb3 Ra7 36.
e5 $16 {/\ Nc5}) (34... b6 35. Ne5 $16) 35. e5+ Ke7 (35... Kd5 $2 36. Rc8 $18 {
[%csl Re8] wins the knight.}) 36. Nc5 Rb6 37. Rd3 $1 {[%csl Re8]} Rxb2 38. Rd7+
Kf8 39. Nxb7 {[%cal Rb7d8,Rb7a5]} Rb3+ (39... Rc2 40. Nxa5 Nc7 41. Rd8+ Ke7 42.
Rd6 $16 {/+- Stohl.}) 40. Kg4 Rb4 41. Nd8 $18 Kg8 42. Re7 $1 f5+ (42... Kf8 43.
Rxf7+ Kg8 44. Re7 Kf8 45. Ra7 $18) 43. Kh5 Kh7 44. Rxe8 Rb2 45. h3 $8 Rh2 46.
Kh4 {[%csl Re6]} 1-0

