1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 {This is the most direct
attempt at keeping the extra pawn. Its obvious drawback is that it weakens the
long diagonal rather early.} 6. a4 $1 {White should not delay this, as after ..
.Bb7 Black could already answer a2-a4 with ...a7-a6, keeping the long diagonal
open.} c6 7. Ne5 Nd5 ({The rare} 7... Bb4+ {speeds up not only Black's
development but also White's. Besides, it weakens the dark squares, making it
a risky choice.} 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ (8... Qxd4 9. Nxc6 $18) 9. Qxd2 Nd5 10. axb5 cxb5
11. Nc3 f6 {Black needs kicking the knight back while this is still possible.}
(11... Ba6 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qb4 $18 {Black's king is stuck in the center, the
d5-pawn is permanently hanging and there is no adequate was to parry Rxa6.})
12. Ng4 Bb7 ({The d5-pawn is more important than the b5-pawn. If} 12... Qd7 13.
Nxd5 exd5 14. Qe3+ Kf8 15. Qf3 Bb7 16. Nxf6 $1 gxf6 17. Qxf6+ Kg8 18. Qg5+ Kf8
19. Ra3 $18) 13. Nxb5 Qd7 {White has retrieved the pawn but his pieces are
hanging a bit, requiring some tactical accuracy.} 14. e4 (14. Nc3 Nxc3 $19) (
14. Qa5 Nc6 15. Qa4 a6 16. Nc3 Nb6 17. Qd1 Nxd4 $17 {Gonzalez Acosta,B (2413)
-Illner,A (2463) Budapest 2012 (0-1, 24)}) 14... Qxb5 15. exd5 Bxd5 ({
Preventing White's next move with} 15... a5 {delays the development up to a
risky degree.} 16. O-O Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Qxd5 18. Ne3 Qb5 19. d5 $36) 16. Ra5 Qb7
17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Qe2+ Kf7 19. O-O Rd8 20. Re1 $14 {With his king exposed and
the queenside underdeveloped Black will most likely lose the d5-pawn, leaving
White with a clear initiative.} Nc6 $6 21. Qe6+ Kf8 22. Nxf6 gxf6 23. Qxf6+ Kg8
24. Rc5 Rac8 25. Rxc6 Qxc6 26. Re6 Qb7 27. Re7 $18) 8. O-O Bb7 {Other moves do
not change White's answer:} (8... f6 {implies an important eakening.} 9. e4 $1
Ne7 10. Nf3 a5 (10... Bb7 {Popov,R (2289)-Tsyrennimaev,V Russia 2007 (1-0, 31)}
11. Bh3 $16) (10... a6 11. b3 cxb3 12. Qxb3 Kf7 13. axb5 cxb5 14. d5 exd5 15.
exd5 Nf5 16. Nc3 Nd6 17. Nd4 $18 {Okkes,M (2375) -Roggeveen,P (2207)
Netherlands 2012 (1-0, 33)}) 11. Qe2 Na6 (11... b4 12. Qxc4 Ba6 13. Qxe6 Bxf1
14. Bxf1 $18) 12. Rd1 Nb4 13. Nc3 $16 {The combined threats axb5, d4-d5 and
e4-e5 offer White very dangerous initiative, especially if we take into
account Black's uncastled king.}) (8... a6 {is likely to transpose to the main
line:} 9. e4 Nf6 {The knight is stable here and it defends the kingside, a
common pattern in all systems based on ...b7-b5.} (9... Nb4 10. Nc3 Nd7 11.
axb5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bb7 {Antic,D (2513)-Ninov,N (2528) Sunny Beach 2009 (½-½,
30)} 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. bxa6 Bxa6 15. Be3 Be7 16. Ra5 O-O 17. Rfa1 $14 {
Material is equal and the position looks symmetrical, but Black's bishops are
passive and exposed.}) (9... Nb6 $6 10. Qf3 Qe7 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Be3 Qf6 13. Qe2
Bb4 14. f4 O-O 15. f5 exf5 {Sokolin,L (2520)-Oll,L (2625) Chicago 1997 (1-0,
29)} 16. exf5 Bxc3 17. bxc3 $18 {/\Ng4}) 10. Nc3 Bb7 {reaching a position
examined below.}) 9. e4 Nf6 (9... Nb4 $6 {leaves the kingside poorly defended
after the thematic} 10. d5 cxd5 11. exd5 Bxd5 12. Nc3 Bxg2 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14.
Kxg2 Ke7 15. axb5 Nd7 16. Nxc4 Kf6 17. Rd1 Nc5 18. Be3 Kf5 19. b6 $18 {
Gedevanishvili,D (2365)-Solomon,S (2395) Sydney 1996 (1-0, 27)}) 10. Nc3 (10.
d5 Be7 {may transpose but it is more logical to develop a piece provoking the
only partly useful ...a7-a6 before breaking in the centre.}) 10... a6 (10... b4
11. Ne2 {dooms the c4-pawn, while Black is not prepared for counterplay in the
centre:} c5 12. d5 exd5 13. exd5 Bxd5 {Hetzer,V (2063)-Valsecchi,A (2360)
Warsaw 2010 (0-1, 45)} 14. Nxf7 $1 Bxf7 (14... Kxf7 15. Nf4 $18) 15. Bxa8 $16)
11. d5 $1 {We are familiar with this central break from a strategic article.
Black's structure on both wings is seriously shaken.} Be7 {This seemingly
modest move is the best chance to keep a playable game, as it consolidates the
kingside.} (11... Bd6 {Jumabayev,R (2555)-Yu,Y (2607) Moscow 2011 (1-0, 43)
leaves the knight vulnerable which White should immediately use with} 12. Ng4
$1 $146 Be7 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. e5 Bxe5 15. dxe6 Qxd1 16. exf7+ Kxf7 17. Rxd1
$16 {Black has problems completing his development and his extra pawn is not
for much use.}) (11... Qb6 $2 {as played in Cori Tello,J (2496)-Fenollar Jorda,
M (2354) Montcada 2012 (1-0, 35) consolidates the queenside but what about the
opposite wing?!} 12. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 13. dxe6+ Kxe6 14. e5 Nd5 {The black king
will soon be helpless against the combined attack of White's pieces and pawns.
One of the winning continuations is} 15. Qg4+ Kf7 16. Qf5+ Ke8 17. Qe6+ Ne7 {
Otherwise the d5-kight would be lost.} 18. Ne4 $18) ({Opening the centre is
worse than playing with fire:} 11... cxd5 $2 12. exd5 exd5 $5 (12... Nxd5 13.
Nxd5 Bxd5 (13... exd5 14. Qh5 g6 15. Nxg6 $18 fxg6 16. Qe5+ {A trick to be
remembered.}) 14. axb5 Bc5 {Sosonko,G (2505)-Chen,T (2285) Buenos Aires 1978 
(½-½, 24)} 15. Bxd5 $1 $146 {The best way to keep White's initiative going.
Exchanges only make Black's delay in development more relevant.} Qxd5 (15...
exd5 16. Bg5 Qd6 17. Nxc4 $18 dxc4 18. Re1+ Kf8 19. Be7+) 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Rd1
Ra7 18. Rxd5 axb5 19. Rxa7 Bxa7 20. Rxb5 $16 {winning the c4-pawn next.}) (
12... b4 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. dxe6+ Ke7 15. Bxb7 $18 {Lopez,M-Mejia,S Guatemala
City 2000 (1-0, 29)}) (12... Bxd5 13. axb5 Bc5 14. Bg5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 $18) 13.
Ng4 $1 $146 {A familiar echange with lethal consequences. The d5-square is
irremediably weak.} Ne4 (13... Be7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Re1+ Kf8 16. Nxd5 $18) (
13... Nbd7 14. Nxd5 $18) (13... Nxg4 14. Qxg4 $18) 14. Ne3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bc5
16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17. Nxd5 O-O 18. axb5 Ra7 19. Be3 Bxe3 (19... Qd6 20. Nb4 Qxd1
21. Rfxd1 Bxe3 22. fxe3 a5 23. Rd4) 20. Nxe3 $16) 12. Nxf7 $5 $146 ({More
effective than the positional approach:} 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Qe2 {with clear
compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Kxf7 13. dxe6+ {The king suddenly appears
being very weakly defended.} Kxe6 (13... Kg8 14. Qxd8+ Bxd8 15. e5 Nd5 16. Ne4
$16) (13... Ke8 14. Bd2 b4 15. e5 bxc3 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. bxc3 $18) 14. Qf3 Nbd7
15. Bf4 b4 16. Rad1 bxc3 17. Bh3+ Kf7 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Bc7+ Nf6 (19... Ke8 20.
Bxd8 Rxd8 21. Qxc3 Nf6 22. Qxc4 $16) 20. Bxd8 Raxd8 21. e5 cxb2 22. Rb1 c3 23.
Qxc3 $16 Nd5 24. Qf3+ Ke8 25. Be6 Rf8 26. Qh5+ g6 27. Qxh7 $18 *

