1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c6 {Before playing ...b7-b5
Black defends the long diagonal.} 6. Ne5 {Since Black deprived himself of the
counterplay with ...c7-c5, this knight jump is well-timed. Otherwise, it would
be harder to prove an advantage after ...b7-b5.} Bb4+ (6... b5 {was held for
playable until Kortschnoj proved an old analysis of his in a modern game:} 7.
Nxc6 (7. a4 {Ribli} Nd5 8. O-O Bb7 9. b3 $36) 7... Qb6 8. Na5 $1 {In his
comments Kortschnoj writes that he had discovered this move after facing this
line in a blitz game against Ulf Andersson.} Nd5 ({The critical line is:} 8...
Qxa5+ 9. Bd2 c3 10. bxc3 Nd5 11. c4 b4 12. cxd5 $16 Bb7 13. Qc2 Bxd5 14. e4 Bb7
15. O-O Be7 16. Rc1 $14 {Ribli}) 9. Bd2 Nc6 (9... Qxd4 $6 10. Nc3 Qc5 11. b4 $1
Qd6 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. O-O Be6 14. e4 $18) (9... b4 $6 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Qc2 Ba6
12. Ne3 $16 {Kortschnoj}) 10. Nxc6 Qxc6 11. e4 $1 {As usual, maintaining a
high rhythm of attack is essential.} Nb4 12. O-O Bb7 13. a4 Nd3 (13... a6 14.
axb5 axb5 15. d5 Qb6 16. Rxa8+ Bxa8 17. dxe6 Qxe6 18. Nc3 $16 {Ribli}) {
Kortschnoj,V (2601)-Moskalenko,V (2551) Barcelona 2004 (1-0, 34)} 14. axb5 Qxb5
15. Ra5 $1 $16 {(Moskalenko)}) (6... c5 {is typical for Line 14 in the
previous database, but White has an extra tempo (even though play is a bit
different than in the main tabiyas after 5...c5).} 7. Na3 cxd4 8. Naxc4 {
By adding ...Nc6, ...Bd7 and 0-0, we reach an important 5...c5 tabiya,
evaluated somewhere between a draw and a slight white advantage.} Bc5 (8...
Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. O-O Ne8 {Khaje Hesamedini,A (2250)-Baeta,M 
(1976) Rio de Janeiro 2016 (1-0, 66)} 12. Na5 $14) (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O {
Ivanisevic,I (2653)-Movsesian,S (2658) Berlin 2015 (1-0, 35)} 10. Qd3 Na6 11.
Rd1 Nb4 12. Qb3 $14) 9. a3 $146 a5 (9... Nbd7 10. b4 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bb6 12. Bb2
O-O 13. O-O Qe7 14. Bxd4 Rd8 15. e3 Bxd4 16. exd4 Nd5 17. Re1 $14) (9... O-O
10. b4 Be7 11. Bb2 $14) 10. Bd2 Nd5 (10... a4 11. Bb4 {more or less retirieves
thae pawn with advantage, for instance} Nbd7 12. Qxd4 $1 Bxd4 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14.
Nxb7+ Qe7 15. Bxe7+ Kxe7 16. Nc6+ Kf8 17. Nxd4 $16) 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1
13. Qxa1 Nxb4 14. Qa4+ N4c6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bf4 Nd7 17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. Bxd6 {
with dangerous initiative. The line still needs testing.}) 7. Nc3 $1 {
Preparing a second pawn sacrifice.} (7. Bd2 Qxd4 8. Bxb4 Qxe5 9. Na3 b5 {
is not entirely clear.}) 7... Nd5 8. O-O $5 ({More dynamic than} 8. Bd2) ({and
} 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qxd4 10. cxb4 Qxa1 11. Nxc4 {which also offer good
compensation.}) 8... Nxc3 (8... b5 9. e4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bd6 (10... Bxc3 11. Qf3
f6 12. Qxc3 fxe5 13. dxe5 $16 {leaves Black vulnerable on dark squares.}) 11.
Qg4 Kf8 12. f4 $16 c5 $2 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. e5 $18 {Quintin Navarro,A (2220)
-Pellicer Cerezuela,M (1794) Aragon 2013 (1-0, 20)}) ({If} 8... Bxc3 $146 9.
bxc3 Nxc3 10. Qc2 {White retrieves one pawn keeping overwhelming initiative on
dark squares.} Qxd4 {runs into} 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. Bb2 {and if} Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2
c3 14. Rad1 Qf6 15. Rd3 $1) (8... O-O 9. Qc2 b5 10. a4 f6 11. Nf3 a5 12. axb5
Bxc3 13. bxc3 cxb5 14. e4 Nc7 15. Rd1 {with strong initiative for the pawn.})
9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Nxc4 O-O $5 ({More material grabbing implies even higher risk:
} 10... Bxa1 11. Ba3 Qxd4 (11... Bb2 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Nxf7 Bxa3 14. Nxd8 Kxd8
15. e4 {/\d5, /\h5. The queen is very dangerous against Black's numerous but
poorly coordinated army.}) 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Nxf7 Qxd1 14. Rxd1+ Ke8 15. Nxh8
Bf6 16. Be4 Nd7 (16... g6 $4 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Bxg6#) 17. Bxh7 c5 18. Bg6+ Kf8
19. Bh5 $16 {Mikhalchishin.}) 11. Rb1 {The bishop is obviously misplaced now.}
b5 (11... Bxd4 12. Ba3 c5 (12... Re8 13. Nd6 $16) 13. e3 Bf6 14. Bxc5 Qxd1 15.
Rfxd1 Rd8 16. Rxd8+ Bxd8 17. Nd6 $16 {retrieves the whole sacrificed material
with obvious advantage.}) (11... Qxd4 12. Ba3 $16 Rd8 13. Qb3 Nd7 14. Rfc1 b5
15. Qxc3 Qxc3 16. Rxc3 bxc4 17. Be7 Re8 18. Bd6 $16 {with complete domination.}
) 12. Ne5 Qxd4 $2 (12... a5 13. Bb2 Bxb2 14. Rxb2 b4 15. Qd2 f6 16. Nxc6 Nxc6
17. Bxc6 Ra7 18. Rc1 Bd7 19. e3 Rc7 20. Rbc2 {"White would keep an advantage,
controlling the c-file." Mikhalchishin.}) 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxc6
Rb8 16. Ba3 $16 {White wins an exchange, Ju,W (2528)-Sachdev,T (2379) Istanbul
2012 (1-0, 39)} *

