1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 {In the past,
the same as now, this is Black's absolute main line against the Catalan. Black
provokes a moment of crisis only after completing the kingside development.} (
6... c5 {is best met with} 7. cxd5 ({White could keep the game within Catalan
territory with the less ambitious} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. a3 dxc4 9. Qc2 {as I
suggested in my English trilogy published at Quality Chess}) 7... exd5 (7...
Nxd5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {exposes Black's minor pieces. One possible plan is} 9. a3 {
Threatening not only b2-b4 but, if the bishop retreats, for example, e2-e4.}
Nc6 10. b4 Be7 11. Bb2 $14) 8. Nc3 {transposing to the Tarrasch defense, a
difficult opening for Black, but which we cannot discuss here due to lack of
space.}) (6... b6 {leads to a difficult version of the Queen's Indian (true, I
tried it with black, but in principle White retains the pressure against the
hanging pawns.} 7. cxd5 exd5 (7... Nxd5 8. e4 Nf6 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Re1 {Black
cannot get counterplay easily as if} c5 11. d5 exd5 12. exd5 Re8 13. Ne5 Bd6
14. Nc4 Bf8 15. Bf4 $16 {Nyback,T (2565)-Berczes,C (2419) Stockholm 2008 (1-0,
31)}) 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Bf4 Na6 10. Rc1 c5 11. dxc5 bxc5 (11... Nxc5 12. Nb5 Ne6
13. Be5 $14 {with nice blockade on d4.}) 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Nd2 $14
{Black cannot prevent Nc4 with annoying pressure against the b6 and d5 pawns.})
(6... Nc6 {usually leads to a nonoptimal Stonewall version for Black:} 7. b3 ({
The careless} 7. Nc3 {allows} dxc4 {transposing to a relatively unfavourable
for White Catalan.}) 7... Ne4 8. Bb2 f5 9. Nc3 Bf6 10. e3 b6 11. Rc1 Bb7 (11...
Ba6 12. Ne1 Qd6 13. Nd3 $14) 12. Ne2 Qd7 13. Nf4 Rfd8 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Ne5 $16
{Nyback,T (2575)-Karlsson,L (2479) Stockholm 2006 (1-0, 35)}) (6... Nbd7 {
[%emt 0:00:01] leads to the closed systems examined in Database}) 7. Qa4 $5 {
This is not the classical treatment of the position but it leads by
transposition to the main line after avoiding a newly discovered black defense
which is not easy to refute. Over the past years I have experimented with two
other interesting variations, but it feels good returning to what used to be
the absolute main line when I started playing the Catalan more than a quarter
of a century ago and in my opinion remains such nowadays, despite fashion's
whims.} (7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 Rb8 12. Qa5
Qc8 13. a4 Rd8 14. Ba3 Rxd4 15. Rfb1 Rb6 16. Bc5 {I had this position a couple
of times, but the following two games made me suspect White's resources are
limited:} Rd7 (16... Rd5 $5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Bd4 Ne4 $13 {Marin,M (2549)
-Vajda,L (2597) Medias 2016 (1-0, 40)}) 17. Rd1 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rb8 19. Bxc6 Bb7
20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Qxa7 Qxa7 22. Bxa7 Ra8 $11 {Feng,M (2162)-Paikidze,N (2369)
Saint Louis 2017 (½-½, 30)}) ({The traditional move order goes} 7. Qc2 {
It would really make sense playing 7.Qc2 if White wants to play} a6 ({One
positive difference with respect to the move order suggested here is that
after the not very topical} 7... c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {White has} 9. Nbd2 $1 Nc6 10.
Nxc4 $16) ({The problematic line mentioned above goes} 7... b5 8. a4 b4 (8...
c6 $2 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Ng5 $18) {and White surely retains pleasant play, but
with a pawn less and a high probability that the game ends in a draw. For
instance:} 9. Nfd2 c6 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 Qh5 13. Nbd2 Ng4 14.
Nf3 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 a5 16. Nc4 Ba6 17. Rac1 Ra7 18. Nfe5 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 Bf6 20.
Qe4 $44 {Gelfand,B (2733)-Ponomariov,R (2743) Olginka 2011 (½-½, 33)}) 8. a4
{which is quite fashionable nowadays. But the following game kind of
disappointed me:} c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nbd2 b5 $5 {WHite has several ways of
playing with a pawn down, but his compensation does not seem to offer more
than equality. And if} 11. axb5 Bb7 12. bxa6 Nxa6 13. Nxc4 Nb4 14. Rxa8 Qxa8
15. Qb3 Bd5 $11 {Marin,M (2529)-Basso,P (2434) Erice 2017 (½-½, 35)}) 7... a6
(7... Bd7 8. Qxc4 Bc6 9. Nc3 {leads to passive play for Black.} Nbd7 10. Re1
Ne4 11. Qd3 Nxc3 (11... f5 12. Qc4) (11... Ndf6 12. Ne5 Nxc3 13. Nxc6 Nxe2+ 14.
Rxe2 bxc6 15. Bxc6 Rb8 16. Rc2 $14) 12. bxc3 f5 13. Nd2 $14 {Riha,V (2270)
-Gizynski,T (2315) Slupsk 1988 (½-½, 37)}) ({Even if circumstances are
slightly better for Black than after 7.Qc2,} 7... c5 {fails equalizing:} 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 (8... Qd5 $146 9. Be3 Bxc5 10. Nc3 Qh5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Nd2 Bd7 13.
Qxc4 Qxc4 14. Nxc4 Bc6 15. e4 $16) 9. Qxc4 Qe7 10. Nc3 h6 {A half-waiting move
preparing ...Nc6 by preventing Bg5.} (10... Nbd7 {is most effectively met by
the rare} 11. Na4 $5 Bd6 12. Rd1 {With his knight on d7 Black has problems
completing his queenside development.} Rd8 13. Be3 Nd5 14. Bd4 $14) ({The
immediate} 10... Nc6 $6 {runs into trouble after} 11. Bg5 {Threatening Ne4.} h6
12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Rfd1 $16 {Miton,K (2601) -Lobanov,S (2365) Wroclaw 2014 (1-0,
53)}) 11. Ne5 ({The simplest, even though the recent kingside weakening makes} 
11. g4 {logical and strong, too.} Nd5 12. g5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 hxg5 14. Nxg5 f6 15.
Ne4 Bb6 16. Qb3 Rd8 17. Ba3 Qc7 18. Rad1 $16 {Izzat,K (2424)-Abdulov,O (2342)
Baku 2015 (1-0, 29)}) 11... Nbd7 12. Nd3 e5 (12... Bd6 13. Nb5 $14) 13. Nxc5
Nxc5 14. Be3 Ne6 15. Rfd1 $16 {Adly,A (2601)-Hussein,A (2392) Doha 2011 (1-0,
43)}) ({Against 7.Qa4} 7... b6 {has become popular over the past time. In
older theory this move simply did not exist! Against our move order it has
been played just a few times, but it needs investigating.} 8. Ne5 {Simple play
based on Qxc4 tends leading to positions with just symbolic white advantage,
as Black plays ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c7-c5.} Qxd4 (8... Nd5 9. Qxc4 Bb7 10.
Rd1 c5 11. e4 Nb4 12. d5 $14) 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 {A similar position arises from the
7.Qc2 b6 line. Black has certain compensation for the exchange as White is not
coordinated yet.} 10. Nc3 $5 $146 {A developing move taking advantage of the
fact that the queen attacks both on a7 and c4. With the queen on c2 this would
make less sense.} (10. Qxa7 {Duzhakov,I (2404)-Gavrilov,A (2465) Pardubice
2016 (1-0, 61)} Bd7 $5 11. Nc3 Nd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bf4 Qe4 14. Qxc7 g5 $13)
10... Nd5 (10... Ba6 {Defending both pawns leads to a position similar to
those arising in the Catalan gambits with the difference that here White has
an extra exchange to compensate for the pawns.} 11. Bf4 Qc5 12. Rad1 b5 {
Not easy to find an active plan for Black.} 13. Qa5 b4 14. Qxc5 Bxc5 15. Ne4
Nxe4 16. Bxe4 c3 17. Bd3 cxb2 18. Bxc7 $14) 11. Bd2 Bc5 12. Qxc4 Ba6 13. Qg4 c6
{An interesting position in which Black will try trapping the bishop.} 14. Rfe1
f5 15. Qf3 Qf6 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Bc3 Qe7 18. e3 Rc8 19. Rac1 Nd7 {It seems as
if the plan has succeeded, but White has resources.} 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. b4 {
Black is best adviced to look for probably insufficient compensation for the
exchange by leaving the bishop on c5, as after} Bd6 22. Qxd5+ Kf8 23. b5 Rc5
24. Bxg7+ Kxg7 25. Rxc5 Bxc5 26. bxa6 {White has a promising position due to
the exposed black king.}) 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {I may repeat myself, but this
is the absolute main Catalan tabiya. White has used the tempi wasted by the
white queen to neutralize the g2-bishop's pressure and gain queenside space.
But in doing so he has weakened several squares along the c-file and also the
a5-square. The outcome of the opening mainly depends on whether Black can
carry out the freeing ...c7-c5 under favorable circumstances. The pawn break
itself not always ensures equality, as White has chances obtaining a promising
ending with an almost symmetrical structure as examined in a strategic article
from this series.} 10. Bd2 {From all developing moves, this is the most
paradoxical, although the by far the most popular and consistent one. White
willingly blocks the knight's access to d2 (in view of the possible Nb3 the
most natural way of developing it). The last move actually starts a
half-waiting game. White intends meeting ...Nbd7 with Ba5 followed by b2-b4
soon, which in most of the cases would offer him a stable advantage as Black
would have little or no counterplay. Playing b2-b4 with the bishop on d2
usually runs into ...Nc6 followed by ...a6-a5 or vice versa, but there are
exceptions, too, when this counterplay does not work out so well. Black has a
wide range of plans, which usually is a sign that there is no clear-cut way to
equality in any of them. Many of the lines examined below look very similar,
but there are small details which change the mutual plans in either case. I
have tried to explain the nuances in detail.} *

