1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qa4 a6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Nbd7 {Before examining the more sophisticated lines, we
should first find out what happens after this natural developing move, against
which 10.Bd2 is mainly directed.} 11. Ba5 Rc8 {The most natural way of
defending the pawn.} (11... Bd6 {creates some concrete problems regarding the
queen's development.} 12. Nbd2 Qe7 {This is the logical consequence of the
previous move but it loses a pawn.} (12... Qe8 {is rather passive:} 13. e4 e5
14. Rad1 $16) 13. Bxc7 Rac8 14. Bxd6 $16) (11... Nb6 12. Nbd2 Rc8 {transposes
to the main line.}) (11... Ra7 12. Nbd2 Qa8 {doesnot offer enough play for the
pawn:} 13. Qxc7 Rc8 (13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Rxc7 15. Bxa8 Rc2 16. Bf3 Rxb2 17.
Rfc1 $14 {leaves White with nicely placed bishops and a strong center .}) (
13... e5 {temporarily retrieves the pawn due to the threat of trapping the
