and planning Nxd4.}) 14. Qf4 Nd5 15. Qg4 $14 {Timmer,R (2295)-Janjgava,L (2490)
Baden-Baden 1991 (½-½, 29) White's coordination is a bit unnatural but so is
Black's.}) 12. Nbd2 {White continues developing, making use of the newly freed
d2-square and waits with b2-b4 until Black unpins his c-pawn.} Nb6 $1 {The
only way of causing White concrete problems on the way of blocking the
queenside with b2-b4. transposes to the main line.} (12... Qe8 {prepares
counterplay in the center, but this is not effective as White has a pawn
majority in that area.} 13. b4 Bd6 (13... Nb8 {is a typical maneuver, aiming
at bothering the bishop and b4-pawn.} 14. a3 Nc6 15. Nb3 Bd6 16. Rfe1 Nxa5 17.
Nxa5 Be4 18. Qb2 Nd5 19. Rac1 Nb6 20. Nd2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 e5 22. e4 Na4 {
Grigoriants,S (2566)-Haldorsen,B (2370) Helsingor 2017 (½-½, 40) White can
keep the balance between the wings with} 23. Qb3 exd4 24. e5 Be7 25. Nc6 $16 {
with complete control.}) ({Another typical plan is} 13... Nd5 14. a3 f5 {
but Black's queenside initiative does not compensate for the weaknesses on e6
and c7.} 15. e4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 Rf6 17. Rfe1 Qh5 {Blomqvist,E (2502)-Ong,K (2320)
Sweden 2009 (1-0, 31)} 18. Rac1 {keeping Black's pieces busy to the defence of
the c7-pawn.} Ba8 19. Qe2 Rh6 20. h3 $16) 14. e4 e5 15. Rfe1 Qe7 16. a3 Rfe8 {
Black has a harmonious development, but his structure is worse, yielding White
an advantage.} 17. Nb3 $146 Ba8 (17... exd4 18. Nfxd4 $16) 18. Rad1 h5 (18...
h6 19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. Nh4 $16) 19. dxe5 Bxe5 (19... Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 21. f4
$18) 20. Ng5 $16) ({With the pawn on b2 still, the regrouping} 12... Nb8 {
bascally loses time.} 13. a3 Nc6 14. Bc3 {A better square than d2, since now ..
.c7-c5 is not an issue. So White has bascally won a tempo.} b4 (14... a5 {
Cramling,P (2550)-Lindberg,B (2406) Stockholm 2008 (1-0, 42)} 15. Ne5 Nxd4 16.
Bxd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qxd4 18. Nc6 Qd7 19. e4 a4 20. Nf3 $16) 15. axb4 Nxb4 16.
Qa4 Bc6 17. Qa5 Rb8 18. Rfc1 Rb5 19. Qa4 Rb8 20. Qd1 Bd5 {Even though Black
will soon manage to ride himself of the weakness on c7, White keeps a
dangerous initiative.} 21. Ne5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 c5 23. dxc5 Bxc5 24. Qa4 $16 Be7
25. Ndf3 Qe8 26. Ne1 Qxa4 27. Rxa4 Rfc8 28. N1d3 Nxd3 29. Nxd3 Rc6 30. Bxf6
Rxc1 31. Bxe7 $18 {Beliavsky,A (2622)-Lautier,J (2682) Odessa 2006 (1-0, 59)})
(12... Bd6 13. e4 e5 {is insufficient for familiar reasons.} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15.
Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Nb3 $16 Bd6 17. Rfe1 Re8 18. Rad1 $18) 13. Rac1 {White has to
live with ...c7-c5, reckoning with the significance of the pin along the a5-d8
diagonal.} ({Black's idea is that the desirable} 13. b4 {runs into} Bxf3 14.
Bxf3 (14. Nxf3 Nc4 {is also insatisfactory.}) 14... Qxd4 {and Black is doing
fine.}) ({Another way of implrementing the main line idea is} 13. Qd3 {The
