(2381) Budva 2013 (1-0, 40)}) 14. Ba5 Bd6 15. Nc3 Bb7 16. Ng5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2
Qa8+ 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 e5 20. e3 {with small but lasting white pressure
in Hammer, J (2633)-Ivanchuk,V (2754) Plovdiv 2010 (1-0, 43)}) (12... Nbd7 13.
Ba5 Qa8 14. Nbd2 Bd5 15. Qe3 Bd6 (15... Rc8 16. b4 Ne8 {Sargissian,G (2670)
-Aveskulov,V (2495) Saratov 2006 (0-1, 62)} 17. Ne5 $5 Bxg2 {The exchange on
e5 would leave the e8-knight passive.} 18. Nxd7 Bd5 19. Rc2 $14) 16. Bh3 Ne4 (
16... Rc8 17. b4 Bf8 18. Rc2 Ne4 19. Rac1 Nxd2 20. Nxd2 $16 {With rigid and
passive play for Black, Grischuk,A (2717)-Zubov,A (2542) Calatrava (rapid)
2007 (1-0, 60)}) 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Ne1 Nb6 {Avrukh,B (2653)-Quesada Perez,Y 
(2505) Beersheba 2005 (1-0, 63)} 19. b3 Ba3 20. Rd1 Rd8 21. Nd3 $14 {White
controls the c5- and e5-squares, making it difficult for Black to break the
center. The e4-bishop is unstable and the a7-rook does not make the position
more appealing.}) 13. e3 Qa8 {This regrouping is also familiar, only that this
time the bishop is more active (and exposed at the same time).} 14. Qd1 b4 {
Preventing Nc3 and creating the plan ...Na5 followed by ...c7-c5 when Black
could use the knight for retrieving the pawn with ...Nb7.} (14... Nb8 {mainly
throws away a tempo:} 15. Ba5 Nc6 16. Be1 Nb8 17. b4 {Everything is ready for
this blocking move now. Black has no favorable way of reacting with ...a6-a5.}
Nbd7 (17... a5 18. Nc3 Bc6 19. a4 bxa4 20. b5 Bb7 21. Nxa4 $16) 18. a4 Nd5 (
18... bxa4 19. Nc3 Bb7 20. Nxa4 $14) 19. Nbd2 Bg6 20. Nb3 Be4 (20... Nxb4 21.
Bxb4 Bxb4 22. Ne5) (20... Bxb4 21. Bxb4 Nxb4 22. Ne5 Qe8 23. Nxg6 fxg6 24. axb5
$16) 21. axb5 Bxb4 (21... axb5 22. Ne5 Nxe5 23. Bxe4 Nc4 24. Na5 $16) 22. Bxb4
Nxb4 23. Nbd2 Bxf3 24. Bxf3 Nd5 25. bxa6 Nb8 (25... Rxa6 26. Rxa6 Qxa6 27. Bxd5
exd5 28. Rxc7 $16) 26. Be2 Nxa6 27. Qa4 Rb8 {Avrukh,B (2633)-Sandipan,C (2546)
Turin 2006 (1-0, 62) The strongest move now is} 28. Nb3 $18 {winning at least
an exchange due to the pin along the a-file.}) (14... Nb4 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. a3
Bd6 17. Nbd2 Bd5 {Smith,A (2484)-Urkedal,F (2469) Norway 2013 (½-½, 37)} 18.
Rc2 $14 {with pleasant pressure along the c-file.}) 15. Qf1 Bd5 (15... Rc8 16.
a3 $146 a5 {The only way to keep the structure compact.} 17. Ne1 $14 {/\Nd3.
After preventing ...Na5 White starts regrouping according to the main plan.})
16. Be1 Rc8 (16... h6 17. Nbd2 a5 {Giri,A (2677)-Khamrakulov,D (2485)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (1-0, 70)} 18. Nc4 Rc8 19. Nfd2 Bxg2 20. Qxg2 a4 21. Ne4
$14) 17. Nbd2 Na5 ({Knights exchange sort of plays into White's hands who
increases his chances for a blockade.} 17... Ne4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Nd2 Bxg2 20.
Qxg2 Na5 21. Nc4 Qxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Nxc4 23. Rxc4 $16 {Gordon,S (2521)-Briscoe,C 
(2253) Hastings 2008 (1-0, 64)}) 18. Ne5 c5 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. Nd3 Bf8 21. Bxd5
Nxd5 {Black has managed exchanging pawns, but White's better coordination
leave him with lasting initiative.} 22. e4 Nb6 (22... Nf6 23. f3 $14) 23. Rxc8
Qxc8 24. Nf3 Qb7 25. Nxb4 Qxe4 26. Qd3 Qxd3 27. Nxd3 Nac4 28. b3 Nd6 29. Rc1
Nd5 30. Rc6 Nf5 31. Ba5 $14 {And Wite eventually won this very pleasant ending,
Kramnik,V (2785)-Leko,P (2755) Moscow 2007 (1-0, 62)} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
