[Black "10...Be4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E05"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "47"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qa4 a6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 {A natural move and quite a difficult to refrain
from as Black activates his bishop with a gain of time. On the other hand, he
needs being aware that he could lose at least as much time when White will
later attack it with Nbd2 or in some cases Nc3.} 11. Qc1 {White places the
queen on the safest square, leaving d1 available for the rook and keeping the
possibility of activating the queen with Qe3 or Qf4 if his bishop moves either
way. Black has tried many moves here. In this section, we will examine those
aiming at preventing Ba5 after the desirable ...Nbd7.} c6 $5 {The history of
this move starts after 2000, even though it has been occasionally played
before. Black mainly intends playing ...Nbd7 followed by ...c6-c5 and keeps a
choice between ...Bd5 and ...Bg6 if White attacks the bishop.} ({The other way
to deny Ba5 is more old-fashioned:} 11... b4 {In principle, a higher
concession than the main move as it weakens the c4-square.} 12. Bg5 {Quite
logical since it clears the knight's path and besides pinning the f6-knight is
an abstractly correct answer to the weakening of the light squares.} Nbd7 13.
Nbd2 Bd5 (13... Bb7 {is more restrictive, when White should transpose to the
main line with} 14. Ne5) 14. Ne5 ({With the given move order} 14. Qc2 {is a
reasonable alternative.} c5 15. e4 Bb7 16. e5 Nd5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. dxc5 Nxc5
19. Nc4 $14 {Polugaevsky,L (2575)-Kristjansson,O (2225) Akureyri 1988 (1-0, 44)
}) 14... Nxe5 ({Black cannot do without this exchange:} 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c5
$6 16. Nc6 Qe8 {Almasi,I (2425)-Donev,I (2400) Austria 1997 (½-½, 23)} 17.
dxc5 $1 Bxc5 18. Bxf6 Rc8 $5 {otherwise Black would have weaknesses on both
wings at no cost for White.} 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Na5 Bxf2 21. Ndc4 Bc5 22. Qf4
$14) 15. dxe5 Ng4 {Play has deviated a bit from White's initial plan, meaning
blocking on c4. Black's knight is on a very bad path now but passive retreats
offer White pressure along the central files.} (15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nd5 17.
Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Rd1 Qd5+ 19. Nf3 $14 {leaves Black with many weaknesses to
defend.}) 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nf3 c5 18. h3 Nh6 {Salov,V (2630)-Short,N (2650)
Amsterdam 1989 (½-½, 45)} 19. g4 $14 {The knight will be out of play for a
long time unless Black weakens his kingside with ...f7-f6.}) ({The familiar
rook lift} 11... Ra7 {is less frequent and not very adequate in this concrete
line.} 12. Rd1 Nbd7 (12... Nc6 13. Bg5 $5 $16 {will offer White a safe
blockade soon.}) 13. Be3 {The rook is suddenly exposed to d4-d5.} Nd5 14. Nc3
Bxf3 (14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $14 {keeps the control over the c5-square and a
stable advantage.}) 15. Bxf3 c6 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. e4 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 $14 {With two
bishops and a strong center, Bruzon Batista, L (2637)-Vaganian, R (2640)
Pamplona 2004 (½-½, 34)}) 12. Rd1 Nbd7 (12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. a4 bxa4
(14... b4 15. Be3 Qe5 {Kolosowski,M (2431)-Staniszewski,P (2419) Poronin 2012 
(½-½, 42)} 16. Bf4 Qc5 17. Qxc5 Bxc5 18. Nd2 Nd5 19. Rac1 Nxf4 20. Rxc5 Nd5
21. Nc4 $14) 15. Na3 {Nyback/Meyer, CD: 'White is in no hurry to capture
Black's pawn on a4, activating the pieces is more important.'} Nbd7 16. Nc4 Ne5
({Nyback/Meyer:} 16... Nd5 17. Rxa4 {was probably a sounder choice for Black.
White has good compensation due to bishop pair and Black's weak pawns, but at
least Black still is a pawn up.}) 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Bf4 Qc5 19. Qxc5 Bxc5 20.
Bxc6 Rad8 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Rxa4 Nd5 {It is understandable that Black tries
neutralizing at least one of the bishops, as otherwise, the b-pawn would
become too strong.} ({Nyback/Meyer:} 22... Ng4 23. Kg2 $1) 23. Bxd5 Rxd5 24.
Rxa6 $14 {White has won a pawn and eventually converted it, Nyback, T (2579)
-Rozentalis, E (2567) Germany 2007 (1-0, 47)}) 13. Nc3 {This is not the
typical square for the knight, but in exchange the enemy bishop will have to
retreat on a nontypical diagonal, too, leaving some undefended queenside
weaknesses.} Bg6 14. a3 $5 {Preparing b2-b4 in case of emergency and
stabilizing the knight.} c5 (14... Qb6 {Cheparinov,I (2682)-Garcia Cardenas,P 
(2405) Antofagasta 2016 (½-½ 54)} 15. Be3 $5 Nd5 16. Bg5 $14 {Black has to
either exchange bishops, with the ensuing weakening of the dark squares, or
weaken his light squares with ...f7-f6, in both cases with the more pleasant
play for White.}) (14... Nd5 15. Nxd5 $5 $146 {Due to the missing bishop from
b7, White's pressure is not easy to neutralize despite the resulting
symmetrical structure.} cxd5 16. Qc6 Ra7 17. Rdc1 Nb8 18. Qc3 Nd7 19. Bf4 $14)
(14... Rc8 $5 $146 {should probably be met with} 15. b4 {The position is not
easy to assess, as engines find it completely equal, despite White's queenside
blockade. I would suggest such a line as at least more pleasant to play with
white:} Nd5 16. Re1 N5b6 17. Bg5 $14) 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Ne5 {One of the moments
when the bishop is really badly missed on the queenside.} cxd4 (16... Rac8 17.
Nc6 $16) 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Bxa8 dxe3 {It may seem that things are going
Black's way, with lots of compensation for the exchange, but White had
calculated better:} 19. Nd5 $1 exf2+ 20. Kf1 Qc5 (20... Qd8 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22.
Bc6 $18) (20... Nxd5 21. Qxc7 Nxc7 22. Rxd7 $16) 21. b4 $1 Qxc1 22. Nxe7+ Kh7
23. Raxc1 Rxa8 24. Kxf2 $16 {Hou,Y (2652)-Hammer,J (2621) Moscow 2017 (1-0, 80)
After simplifications Black only has some chances to hold the ending with a
pawn for the exchange, but not more than that.} *

