1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 ({The following game is not important
for the opening part but can be a model for how to play in the ending arising
in the line with 12...Nbd7 below.} 4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Bg2 a6 7. Nc3 Rb8
8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3 Bb7 10. O-O c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bf4 Rc8 13. Rad1 O-O 14. Ne5
Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Qxd3 17. Rxd3 Rfd8 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20.
Rc1 Be7 21. Nb1 f5 22. e3 Bf6 23. b3 Kf8 24. Kf3 Ke7 25. h3 Rd5 26. Ke2 Kd7 27.
Nd2 Be7 28. Nf3 Bf6 29. Ne1 Rd6 30. g4 fxg4 31. hxg4 Rc6 32. Rxc6 Kxc6 33. Nd3
a5 34. e4 a4 35. Ke3 axb3 36. axb3 Kd6 37. Kf4 Bd8 38. g5 Ke7 39. Kg4 Kf8 40.
f3 f6 41. Kh5 fxg5 42. Kh6 Kg8 43. Nc5 Kf7 44. Kxh7 Bb6 45. Nd3 Kf6 46. Kg8 Bg1
47. Kf8 e5 48. Ke8 Ke6 49. Kd8 Kd6 50. Kc8 Be3 51. Kb7 Bd4 52. b4 Kd7 53. Nc5+
Kd6 54. Kb6 Bc3 55. Kxb5 Bd2 56. Nb7+ Kc7 57. Na5 Be3 58. Ka6 {1-0 (58)
Andersson,U (2623)-Ivanov,S (2538) Sweden 2000}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2
a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 11. Qc1 Qc8 {One of the oldest
sub-divisions of 10...Be4 which has not lost its actuality up to today. Black
sustains the thematic ...c7-c5 while also preparing ...Nbd7 without allowing
the pin with Ba5.} 12. Bg5 {The logical reaction since the knight is less well
defended now. This will make itself felt when Black will break in the center.}
c5 ({The alternative is preparing a bit more this pawn break, which also
allows White getting developed with a gain of time, though.} 12... Nbd7 13.
Nbd2 Bb7 (13... Bd5 14. e4 Bb7 15. e5 Nd5 16. Ne4 $14) 14. Ne5 ({As logical as
it looks,} 14. Nb3 {does not offer much:} a5 15. Rd1 Bd5 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2
a4 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Bxf6 Bb6 $1 {with a solid position for Black in Gelfand, B
(2733)-Leko, P (2751) Mexico City 2007 (½-½, 24).}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c5
16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. dxc5 Qd5+ 18. Nf3 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Bxc5 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Rfc1
Rfc8 22. Rc2 {For this type of ending, just slightly better for White, but
with considerable chances to outplay the opponent in the long run, kindly
consult the game inserted in the beginning of the line.} Bf8 (22... Rc7 23.
Rac1 Rac8 24. Ne1 f5 25. Nd3 Bd6 26. Rxc7 Rxc7 27. Rxc7 Bxc7 28. Nb4 a5 29. Nc2
$14 {and Black will soon be forced to place his second queenside pawn on a
dark square.}) 23. Rac1 Rxc2 24. Rxc2 Rd8 25. Ne1 Rd4 26. f4 (26. Nd3 Rc4 $1 {
Esposito,L (2277)-De Filomeno,S (2385) Civitanova Marche 2013 (½-½, 36)})
26... Kg7 27. Kf3 f5 28. Nd3 $14) 13. Nbd2 ({The most popular move, but} 13.
dxc5 {also deserves being mentioned:} Qxc5 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 (15...
Bxf6 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qc7 Be4 19. Ne5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 $16 {Freitag,
M (2384)-Smideliusz,M (2044) Oberwart 2011 (1-0, 36)}) 16. Rd1 Bxf3 17. Bxf3
Ra7 18. a4 b4 19. Ne4 $14) 13... Bb7 (13... Bd5 $6 {offers White a tempo for
free:} 14. e4 $1 Bb7 15. e5 Nd5 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. dxc5 Nd7 18. b4 $16) 14. dxc5
Qxc5 15. Nb3 {Playing for initiative.} ({This looks more accurate than} 15.
Qxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 {when White seems to have too many knights for this
type of ending.}) 15... Qb6 (15... Qc8 16. Rd1 Bd5 {Smejkal,J (2545)
-Prandstetter,E (2435) Sumperk 1984 (½-½, 34)} 17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $14 {
With an advance in development and black queenside weaknesses.}) (15... Qxc1
16. Raxc1 Bd5 17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 h6 {Fomichenko,E (2458)-De Schampheleire,G
(2254) Brasschaat 2010 (1-0, 36)} 19. Bd2 $14 {With pleasant control on the
queenside.}) 16. Rd1 Bd5 17. Ne5 $5 $146 {Once again heading for a symmetrical,
but slightly better for White, ending.} Bxg2 18. Kxg2 h6 19. Be3 Qb7+ 20. f3
$14 {Black is still struggling with his development.} *

