1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 11. Qc1 Nc6 {If compared with 10...Nc6, this
old-fashioned move has the drawback of cutting the bishop's retreat. Besides,
with his queen on c1, White can do better than 12.e3, as the bishop enjoys her
support.} 12. Be3 $1 Rc8 {This seems to be a flexible move, adding latent
pressure against the white queen before undertaking anything concrete, but
arranging ...c7-c5 proves uneasy, as the queen's knight and bishop experience
some problems of space. More concrete approach is not more effective either.} (
12... Nb4 {offers White a later tempo with a2-a3, allowing him stabilizing the
position.} 13. Nbd2 Bd5 (13... Bb7 14. Bg5 Rc8 15. a3 Nbd5 16. b4 $5 a5 17. e4
Nb6 18. bxa5 Na4 19. e5 Nd7 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Qb1 Ba6 22. Ne4 h6 23. Qb4 c5 24.
dxc5 Ndxc5 25. Rfd1 $18 {Sosonko Gennadi-Zuckerman Bernard/New York (USA) 1984
(1-0, 42)}) 14. Bg5 $5 $146 Nxa2 (14... Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Qf4
f5 18. Rac1 $14) 15. Rxa2 Bxa2 16. b3 $14) ({Heading for exchanging the
apparently exposed white minor pieces leave the c6-knight in trouble.} 12...
Ng4 $2 13. Nc3 $16 Bxf3 $2 (13... Nxe3 14. Nxe4 Nxf1 15. Qxc6 $18) 14. Bxf3
Nxe3 15. fxe3 Qd6 16. Ne4 Qd7 17. Nc5 $18 {winning at least an exchange.}) (
12... Na5 {This is not a very stable square for the knight.} 13. Nbd2 Bd5 14.
Qc3 {This gains a tempo on the way to stabilize the queenside to White's
favour.} Nb7 (14... b4 {only weakens the queenside.} 15. Qd3 Qb8 16. Rfc1 Rc8
17. Bg5 h6 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Ne4 $16 {Cernousek,L (2428)-Talla,V (2388) Banska
Stiavnica 2012 (1-0, 47)}) 15. Rfc1 Rc8 16. b4 Qd6 17. a3 a5 18. Bf4 Qa6 19.
Ne5 $16 {Haba,P (2570)-Michenka,J (2396) Czechia 2008 (½-½, 38)}) 13. Nbd2
Bd5 14. Rd1 Ng4 {At this height of the game the most constructive move, aiming
at weakening White's control over c5.} (14... Na5 {leads to familir play.} 15.
Qc3 b4 $6 16. Qd3 Bb7 17. Rac1 Ng4 18. Ne4 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Bd5 20. b3 Nb7 21. Ne5
$16 {Smejkal,J (2560)-Gligoric,S (2505) Vrsac 1983 (1-0, 43)}) 15. Nb3 Nb4 (
15... Bxb3 $5 16. axb3 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Nb4 $14 {offfers some chances to defend
the fortress, but leads to one-sided play where only White can display active
plans, due to Black's weaknesses along the a- and c-files.}) 16. Bd2 Nf6 (16...
Nxa2 17. Qc2 Nb4 18. Bxb4 Bxb4 19. Rxa6 $14) (16... c5 $5 $146 {leads to
interesting play, but with accurate play, White can keep the more pleasant
position:} 17. Nxc5 Bxf3 18. Bxb4 (18. Bxf3 Qxd4 19. Be3 Qe5 20. Bxg4 Bxc5)
18... Bxg2 19. Kxg2 a5 20. Be1 e5 21. Qc3 b4 22. Qf3 exd4 23. Nd3 $14 {Black's
pawns on the left half of the board are vulnerable.}) 17. Nc5 Nc6 (17... Bxf3
18. Bxf3 Qxd4 19. Bxb4 Qxb4 20. Nxa6 Qa4 21. Bb7 $16) 18. Be3 (18. Bg5 $5 $14)
18... Bxc5 19. Qxc5 Ne4 20. Qc2 Nb4 21. Qb1 Nf6 22. Bg5 $1 h6 23. Bxf6 Qxf6 24.
a3 Bxf3 25. Bxf3 $16 {Black's attempts at counterplay have left him with just
weaknesses, Agzamov, G-Gligoric, S/Vrsac 1983 (1-0, 47)} *

