1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 11. Qc1 Nbd7 {Black mainly aims to almost transpose
to Line 6, with the difference that his bishop will be on a8, not on b7. It
might mean that White would have less casual tricks.} 12. Ba5 Rc8 (12... Ra7 {
does not change the evaluation nor the plans.} 13. Nbd2 Bd5 14. Re1 Ne4 15.
Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qe3 Qa8 (16... Ba8 17. Rac1 $16) 17. Rac1 (17. Ne5 $5 Bxg2 18.
Nxd7 Rd8 19. Ne5 Bd5 20. Rac1 $14) 17... Rc8 18. Red1 Bd6 19. Bh3 Bd5 20. Ne5
$14 {Ulybin,M (2538)-Bogosavljevic,B (2548) Paracin 2011 (1-0, 35)}) 13. Nbd2
Ba8 14. a3 $5 {This move was inspired to me by 12.a3 in Line 12. White
prepares b2-b4 with all the comfort while also preparing for some cases an
alternative way of doubling major pieces on the c-file.} ({One of the reasons
for not going along the line planned by Black is that after} 14. Qc2 Nb6 15.
Rac1 c5 16. Qd3 Nfd7 {White does not have Ng5 anymore and Black seems to be
quite well regrouped.}) 14... Ne4 {Now or later Black needs using the fact
that White does not control the e4-square as in the 10...Nbd7 lines. Otherwise,
the play would soon be similar, with the usual space advantage and queenside
blockade.} (14... Qe8 15. b4 Bd6 16. Re1 Ne4 17. Ra2 $1 {I had discovered this
plan decades ago when Suba first talked to me about the a2-a3 idea. White
plans Rc2.} f5 18. Rc2 Nb6 19. Qa1 Bd5 20. Rec1 $14 Qd7 21. Bxb6 $5 cxb6 22.
Ne5 Bxe5 23. dxe5 Rxc2 24. Rxc2 Rc8 25. Qc1 Rxc2 26. Qxc2 Nxd2 27. Qxd2 {
Despite simplifications, Black's position remains difficult.} Bc6 28. Qd6 Qxd6
29. exd6 Bd7 30. e4 fxe4 31. Bxe4 $16 {and White won in Beliavsky, A (2652)
-Kovacs,G (2385) Hungary 2003 (1-0, 46)}) 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qe3 {An important
move, gaining time for controlling the c-file with the rooks. This way, White
will not need playing b2-b4 to stabilize the queenside.} Nf6 {The most active
move.} (16... f5 17. Nd2 $16) (16... Bd5 17. Rac1 Nf6 (17... Bd6 18. Nd2 $14)
18. Ne5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qd5+ 20. Qf3 $1 Qxf3+ (20... Qxd4 $140 21. Nc6 Qd7 22.
Na7 $16) (20... c5 21. Qxd5 exd5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. Rc2 $16) 21. Kxf3 c5 22.
dxc5 Bxc5 23. Rc2 $14 {with the usually pleasant ending for White.}) 17. Rac1
Bd6 18. Ne5 $1 ({Due to Black's stability on light squares and the previous
minor piece exchange,} 18. b4 {restricts White's possibilities.} Qe8 19. Rfe1
Bd5 {Thomas,M-Shishkin,V LSS email 2007 (½-½, 23)}) 18... Bxe5 (18... Bxg2
19. Kxg2 Nd5 20. Qb3 Bxe5 21. dxe5 {/\Rc6, e4} Qg5 22. f4 Qg4 23. Qf3 Qxf3+ 24.
Rxf3 c5 25. b3 $5 $16 {/\e4, Rfc3}) 19. dxe5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 {The impression
that Black will have a good knight versus a potentially bad bishop is not real.
There is no stability for the knight on d5 and Black has weaknesses along the
c-file. Besides, his queen has little chances for activity.} Qd5+ (20... Nd5
21. Qe4 Qe8 (21... Qe7 22. Rc6 $16) 22. Rc5 $16) 21. Kg1 Ng4 22. Qf4 Nxe5 23.
e4 {Forcing the transposition to a promising ending.} Qd6 24. Rfd1 Ng6 25. Qxd6
cxd6 26. Rxc8 Rxc8 27. Rxd6 $16 {Black will have to keep his rook passive on
a8 or else lose a pawn without compensation.]} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
