[White "Line 12 Open system"]
[Black "11...Bb7"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E05"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "79"]
[EventDate "2018.01.11"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 11. Qc1 Bb7 $5 {A paradoxical retreat, introduced by
Karpov during his first match with Kasparov. Since the bishop will have to
retreat soon anyway, why not do it at once? Besides, Black tries proving that
White is in some sort of Zugzwang and openly invites him to a draw by
repetition.} 12. a3 $5 {This is the idea Suba had shown me sometime in the
early '90s. The ideas are similar to those explained in line 11. Since b2-b4
is an essential part of White's plan, a2-a3 is no less useful than, say, the
natural 12.Rd1. In some cases, a2-a3 makes b2-b4 playable even with the bishop
on d2, as White is better prepared against ...a6-a5. Finally, White may
consider increasing the pressure along the c-file with Ra2-c2.} Nbd7 ({Under
the changed circumstances, the plan based on} 12... Qc8 {is not too effective.
White has at least two viable answers.} 13. Bb4 {This positional pawn
sacrifice, aiming at consolidating the control over the dark squares, is my
favorite.} ({The most popular move is} 13. b4 {though.} a5 14. bxa5 Nc6 15. Qb2
{An important detail is that Black does not have 15...b4, so he cannot
retrieve the pawn with all the comfort.} Nxa5 16. Qxb5 {However, things would
not have been entirely clear in Rodshtein,M (2609)-Giri,A (2672) Biel 2010 
(1-0, 39) if Black had played} c6 17. Qb2 c5 {when his queenside initiative
might have compensated for the missing pawn.}) 13... Bxb4 14. axb4 Nc6 {
Cmilyte,V (2498)-Xu,Y (2479) Dagomys 2009 (½-½, 49)} 15. Qc3 Nd5 16. Qb3
Ndxb4 17. Nc3 Qd8 18. Rfc1 Qe7 19. Ne4 {with fantastic compensation for the
pawn.}) ({If} 12... Bd6 {the best reaction is already} 13. b4 (13. Bb4 {
is less effective as after} Bxb4 14. axb4 Nc6 15. Qc3 Ne4 {the black queen
adds pressure on d4, forcing} 16. Qe3 Nxb4 {when Black grabs the pawn under
much better circumstances than in the previous line.}) 13... a5 $146 {This
untested move is actually critical.} (13... Nbd7 {is too static to equalize.}
14. Bc3 Nb6 15. Nbd2 Ne4 16. Nb3 Nc4 17. Qc2 $14 {Bogner,S (2565)-Karavade,E 
(2398) Caleta 2015 (½-½, 47)}) 14. bxa5 Nc6 15. Nc3 Nxa5 (15... Rxa5 16. Qb2
Na7 17. e4 Qa8 18. d5 exd5 19. Nxd5 $16) 16. Rb1 c6 {With ...Qc8 instead of ...
Bd6 this position would offer Black normal play as he would have chances for
counterplay with ...Nc4 and ...c5. But here his queen is less active and the
pin after} 17. Bg5 $14 {is molesting, offering White time to take measures
against the queenside break.}) 13. Ba5 Rc8 (13... Bd6 14. Nbd2 Qc8 15. b4 e5
16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Bxe5 19. Ra2 Bd6 20. Rc2 $14 {Kachiani
Gersinska,K (2416)-Seps,M (2173) Gothenburg 2005 (1-0, 41)}) 14. Nbd2 Qe8 15.
b4 Ne4 {This pattern is familiar to us from line 13. In order to get chances
for equalizing Black needs using White's weaker control over e4.} 16. Nxe4 ({
I would consider here} 16. Ra2 $5 {with similar ideas as in Line 11.}) 16...
Bxe4 17. Qe3 Bd5 18. Rac1 Bd6 19. Ne5 f5 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. f4 {The position
has stabilized and the course of the game shows that White keeps more
possibilities for active play.} Nf6 22. Rc2 c6 23. Rfc1 h5 24. Bb6 Bxe5 25.
dxe5 Ne4 26. Bd4 Qg6 27. Kh1 Rfe8 28. a4 {Opening a new front.} Re6 29. axb5
axb5 30. Ra2 Rc7 31. Qf3 Kh7 32. Rg1 {One rook threatens intruding along the
a-file, the other one inhibits Black's attack.} Qf7 33. h3 Rh6 34. Kh2 Qe7 35.
Qb3 Qe8 36. Ra6 Qe6 37. Ra8 g5 38. Qe3 Rg7 39. fxg5 Rxg5 {In Suba,M (2525)
-Psakhis, L (2605) Andorra 1994 (0-1, 62) White gradually let things out of
control and lost.} 40. Qf4 $16 {followed by Be3 and Qh4 would have put Black
in a critical situation.]} *

